    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_23_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                        <note>39</note>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth Town</placeName>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
                        <date when="1810-04-23">April 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date></dateline></opener> <note>90</note>
                  
                   <p>
                       My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir,</persName> and kind critic, <hi rend="underline">Why</hi> you<lb/>
                       should bestow so much of your <choice><orig>inestima<lb/>
                       ble</orig><reg>inestimable</reg></choice> time upon us is a question which I<lb/>
                       cannot answer. To attribute it to your<lb/>
                       good nature would be sinning against<lb/>
                       the fundamental principles of our sect<lb/>
                       which takes utility for its basis, to say that<lb/>
                       it was occasioned by our own deservings<lb/>
                       would be truly monstrous - So I will accept<lb/>
                       it purely as a favour &amp; as a great favour<lb/>
                       I consider it.<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        The only return in my power for your<lb/>
                        kindness is to shew you that it has not<lb/>
                        been thrown away; I therefore trouble you<lb/>
                        with the enclosed, not to encroach one<lb/>
                        minute more upon your leisure but<lb/>
                        to shew that I &amp; my little sect have<lb/>
                        spared no pains to improve the Chapter on<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_23_page02.jpg"/>
                        on statesmen from the judicious &amp; <choice><orig>com-<lb/>
                        prehensive</orig><reg>comprehensive</reg></choice> remarks you had made.<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        Beside the obligation which <del>you</del><lb/>
                        I feel from the sacrifice you have made<lb/>
                        of your labor &amp; skill I have to redouble<lb/>
                        my thanks for your turning your thoughts<lb/>
                        towards us at a moment of the tenderest<lb/>
                        interest - I have also to thank you for<lb/>
                        your kindness, your condescenscion <choice><orig>to.<lb/>
                        wards</orig><reg>towards</reg></choice> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> - His mind is open to <choice><orig>know.<lb/>
                        ledge</orig><reg>knowledge</reg></choice> &amp; counsel (and <add><unclear/></add> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> <del>adds</del><add>interpolates</add> he is of a most <choice><orig>affec.<lb/>
                        tionate</orig><reg>affectionate</reg></choice> temper)- you know my agriculture<lb/>
                        for mental soil is to prepare it for the<lb/>
                        reception of good seed more than to<lb/>
                        plant it with any peculiar crop - To be<lb/>
                        able to think &amp; to take pleasure in the<lb/>
                        exercise of thought is not very common<lb/>
                        at present, every body remembers &amp; quotes<lb/>
                        - few reflect -<lb/></p>
                    <closer>
                        Your truly obliged friend<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lovell Edgeworth</persName><lb/></closer>
                    
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_23_page03.jpg"/>
                <note>40</note>
                <postscript><p>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> is much flattered by your message to her<lb/>
                        but she says she can consider it only as a polite<lb/>
                        compliment till she sees you here<lb/></p></postscript>
                    
                <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1810_04_23_page04.jpg"/>
                <closer>
                        To<lb/>
                        <address>
                            <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">E. Dumont Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>,</persName><addrLine/>
                            <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Haymarket-19_ENK">19. Haymarket-</placeName> <addrLine/></address>
                    </closer>
                    
                
                
                
